INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','page',0,1134,2465,'und',0,'<h2>Eyes on the Prize</h2><p>Three Achieving the Dream Institutions&mdash;Mott Community College, Southwest Texas Junior College, and Valencia Community College&mdash;were recognized for their extraordinary efforts and demonstrable improvements in student outcomes, by being named three of the ten finalists in the Aspen Prize for Community College Excellence. These institutions now enter the last stage of the competition for the $1 million prize. <a href=\"http://www.aspeninstitute.org/news/2011/09/13/aspen-institute-names-america-s-ten-finalist-community-colleges-first-ever-1-million\" target=\"_blank\">Read more about the ten community college finalists named for the $1 million Aspen Prize Fund</a>.</p><h2>$25,000 Leah Meyer Austin Award</h2><p>Lumina Foundation, Achieving the Dream, Inc., and the American Association of Community Colleges (AACC) are pleased to announce applications for the 2012 Leah Meyer Austin Institutional Student Success Leadership Award are now being accepted. The $25,000 award is open solely to institutions actively affiliated with Achieving the Dream.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','person',0,1144,8116,'und',0,'<p>Jazmin Lopez is the Executive Assistant to the President and CEO for Achieving the Dream, Inc.&nbsp; In this role, Lopez manages the schedule and travel of the President and CEO, performs research, and supports overall operations. &nbsp;</p><p>Lopez first joined Achieving the Dream as the Graduate Program and Policy Intern and was quickly promoted to Administrative Assistant, providing support to the program and operations teams, all while managing a full course load in pursuit of her Master&rsquo;s in Education Policy at George Washington University.&nbsp;</p><p>She brings with her experience working as a teacher&rsquo;s assistant in several public schools in Durham, North Carolina and New York City. Her interests include race and ethnic studies, urban education policy, and higher education. She is a graduate of Prep for Prep, a leadership development program that prepares young students for placement in independent schools throughout New York City.</p><p>Educational Background: Lopez recently graduated from Duke University with a Bachelor&rsquo;s of Arts in Sociology and minor in Visual Studies, and is currently pursuing a Master&rsquo;s degree in Education from George Washington University.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','person',0,1145,3503,'und',0,'<p>Laurece Summers is the Assistant Director of Finance for Achieving the Dream, Inc. In this role, Summers partners with the Associate Director of Finance and the Associate Director of Programs to ensure that all financials and reports meet the guidelines issued to or requested by the funders.</p><p>Prior to joining Achieving the Dream, Summers served as a Compliance Associate for MDC, an Achieving the Dream Founding Partner and former Managing Partner. While at MDC, she worked on various projects, including creating methods to manage narrative reports and financials, and &nbsp;reviewing and reconciling college financials to ensure that their spending and budget were in alignment with the requests of funders. Previously, Summers served as Executive Assistant at PricewaterhouseCoopers, where she worked in the auditing division, updating and coordinating financial statements for the auditors.</p><p>Summers has been recognized for her outstanding scholastic accomplishments; she was awarded the 2005 Opportunity Scholarship by GlaxoSmithKline and was acknowledged in 2003 for making the President&rsquo;s list.</p><p>Educational Background: Summers holds a Bachelor of Science in Accounting and Business Administration from North Carolina Wesleyan College. She is currently pursuing certification to become a Certified Public Accountant.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','person',0,1147,9625,'und',0,'<p>Debbie Werden is the Associate Director of Finance for Achieving the Dream, Inc.&nbsp; In this role, Werden oversees general accounting and financial reporting for this national nonprofit. She implements accounting procedures, policies, and practices to ensure accurate and timely financial measurement and reporting.</p><p>Werden has over 18 years of finance experience, 11 of which are in nonprofit accounting. Her specialties include full cycle accounting, budget preparation and forecast analysis, financial management reports, policy and procedure development, and audit/tax return preparation.&nbsp;Prior to her role with Achieving the Dream, Werden served as Accounting Manager for two local Maryland foundations, Senior Accountant for a nonprofit CPA consulting firm, and Financial Accounting Manager for a national association.&nbsp;</p><p>Werden has professional training and extensive computer software experience with financial databases, billing, and payroll processing.</p><p>Educational Background: Werden holds a Bachelor of Science degree in Accounting from the University of Maryland- College Park.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','page',0,1149,2493,'und',0,'<p>Welcome to our Newsroom where you&#39;ll find helpful facts and updated information about Achieving the Dream and the national student success and completion agenda. Our staff is here to assist you, so if you have any media requests, please contact:</p><p>Lauren Lewis<br />Assistant Director of Communications<br /><a href=\"mailto:LLewis@AchievingtheDream.org\">LLewis@AchievingtheDream.org</a><br />(240) 450-3817 (direct)<br />(917) 613-6419 (cell)</p><p>Learn More</p><ul><li><a href=\"/about/newsroom/press_releases\">Press Releases</a></li><li><a href=\"/news/atd_newsletters\">Newsletters</a></li><li><a href=\"/news/in_the_news\">Media Coverage</a></li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','person',0,1151,2776,'und',0,'<p><em>Director, Center for Community College Student Engagement<br />Faculty, Community College Leadership Program (CCLP)</em><br /><br />Kay McClenney is Director of the Center for Community College Student Engagement and a faculty member in the Community College Leadership Program (CCLP) at The University of Texas at Austin. The Center conducts the Community College Survey of Student Engagement (CCSSE) and the Survey of Entering Student Engagement (SENSE) and has now surveyed nearly two million community college students at over 800 colleges in 50 states. Dr. McClenney also directs the Center&rsquo;s Initiative on Student Success, a long-term student focus group research initiative supported by the MetLife Foundation and Houston Endowment Inc.</p><p>Also within the CCLP, she is senior consultant to the UT/CCLP Achieving the Dream work and co-director of Student Success BY THE NUMBERS, funded by the Greater Texas Foundation. She was co-director of CLASS ─ the California Leadership Alliance for Student Success and of the national Bridges to Opportunity initiative. She previously served for 10 years as Vice President and chief operating officer of the Education Commission of the States.</p><p>Dr. McClenney has served as a consultant to education institutions, state higher education systems, state government, and professional associations in 47 states and internationally. In addition, she served for a number of years as a community college educator, during which she was a faculty member, program director, system administrator, and interim CEO. A frequent keynote speaker, Dr. McClenney also has authored numerous publications on education issues, strategic planning, accountability, student success and leadership.&nbsp;</p><p>Dr. McClenney has served as a member of the Board of Directors of the American Association of Community Colleges (AACC) and the Executive Board of the American Association of Women in Community Colleges (AAWCC). She received the 2002 PBS O&rsquo;Banion Prize for contributions to teaching and learning in America, the 2009 Mildred Bulpitt Woman of the Year Award from the American Association of Women in Community Colleges, the 2009 International Leadership Award from NISOD, and the 2011 National Leadership Award from AACC. She co-chairs AACC&rsquo;s 21st Century Commission on the Future of Community Colleges.</p><p>Educational Background: Dr. McClenney earned her Ph.D. in educational administration from the Community College Leadership Program at The University of Texas at Austin. Her previous degrees are a B.A. from Trinity University and an M.A. in Psychology from Texas Christian University.&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1153,3576,'und',0,'<p>Across the nation, state governments and private foundations are pursuing the long-elusive goal of improving college completion rates. Driving these efforts is a growing awareness of the large proportion of students who come to college&mdash;especially community college&mdash;unprepared for college-level coursework. This challenge is one that the states and colleges involved in Achieving the Dream and its <em>Developmental Education Initiative</em> have been addressing for several years.</p><p>Now states are turning to a familiar tool in education reform&mdash;assessment&mdash;as a valuable lever to improve college readiness. <em>Testing Ground</em> describes how Florida&rsquo;s Division of Colleges worked with K-12 partners to design, plan, and launch an ambitious college-readiness agenda with a new college placement test as its centerpiece. By using data to create a sense of urgency, making faculty central players, and ensuring that prominent champions keep the efforts alive, Florida&rsquo;s education system is well on its way to implementing major college-readiness reforms.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1154,2589,'und',0,'<p>Substantive and innovative policy changes designed to help students succeed in developmental education are underway in the six states involved with the <em>Developmental Education Initiative</em> (DEI), even in the face of challenging economic times.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1155,3578,'und',0,'<p>Our nation can only meet its ambitious college completion goals if&nbsp;students who start in developmental education succeed. Virginia&mdash;like nearly every state and, indeed, many countries&mdash;has therefore turned its attention to helping more students prepare more effectively and efficiently for college-level work.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','news',0,1156,2591,'und',0,'<p>Fewer than 45 percent of college-ready students and just 20 percent of remedial students earn a certificate or degree in four years at <a href=\"http://valenciacollege.edu/\">Valencia College</a> in Orlando, Fla. That&#39;s &quot;nearly three times the rate&quot; of similar urban community colleges...</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1158,8599,'und',0,'<p>An interim report from MDRC and the Community College Research Center that examines the experiences of the first 26 colleges to join the Achieving the Dream Network. The study looks at the influence of Achieving the Dream in its early stages while its practices and supports were still evolving.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','person',0,1178,2709,'und',0,'<p><em>Assistant Professor, University of Virginia</em></p><p>Dr. Heather Wathington is an assistant professor of education at the Curry School of Education at the University of Virginia, and a Data Coach for Achieving the Dream. As an Achieving the Dream Data Coach, Dr. Wathington consults three community colleges and one historically Black institution with an interest in improving their student retention and graduation rates, particularly for low-income students and students of color. Her research focuses on the academic achievement of low-income students and students of color in higher education, with a specific focus on understanding the educational contexts, levers, and practices that promote greater academic success for these students.</p><p>Much of her current work is part of The National Center for Postsecondary Research (NCPR). Funded by the Institute of Education Sciences of the Department of Education, NCPR was established in 2006 to study the effectiveness of programs designed to help underprepared students advance to a degree. The Center is a collaborative partnership with the Community College Research Center in Teachers College at Columbia University, MDRC, University of Virginia, and a professor at Harvard University. The Center has published a series of reports detailing how learning communities and summer accelerated bridge programs affect the academic outcomes of developmental students. In addition to conducting research and teaching, Dr. Wathington serves as the Board Chair for the Maya Angelou Schools in Washington, DC. The Maya Angelou Schools are a multi-campus collaboration of charter schools and schools for disconnected youth dedicated to empowering young people to reach their potential and to transition to college, career, and a lifetime of success.</p><p>Prior to her appointment at the University of Virginia, Dr. Wathington served as senior research officer at Lumina Foundation for Education. Before joining the Lumina Foundation, she served as director of programs in the office of Diversity, Equity, and Global Initiatives at the Association of American Colleges and Universities (AAC&amp;U) in Washington, D.C.</p><p>Educational Background: Dr. Wathington is an honors graduate of Wellesley College in Wellesley, Massachusetts, and earned a master&#39;s degree in higher education management from the University of Pennsylvania. She has her doctorate from the University of Michigan in Higher and Postsecondary Education.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','press_release',0,1179,2645,'und',0,'<p><strong>Achieving The Dream </strong>(<a href=\"http://www.achievingthedream.org/\">www.achievingthedream.org</a>), in partnership with CompletionMatters.org, a project of ISKME (<a href=\"http://www.iskme.org/\">www.iskme.org</a>) and StudentMentor.org, challenges community college students enrolled in Achieving the Dream Institutions nationwide to tell their stories, in three minutes or less, for the chance to win prizes such as iPads, tuition scholarships, school supplies, and Amazon Gift Cards.&nbsp; Winners will be announced at <strong><ins cite=\"mailto:kloovis\" datetime=\"2012-01-17T18:53\"><a href=\"http://www.achievingthedream.org/get_involved/events\">D.R.E.A.M.</a></ins><ins cite=\"mailto:kloovis\" datetime=\"2012-01-17T18:52\"> (</ins></strong>Achieving the Dream&rsquo;s 2012 <ins cite=\"mailto:kloovis\" datetime=\"2012-01-17T18:53\">Annual Meeting on Student Success)</ins>, taking place February 28-March 2, 2012 at the Hyatt Regency in Dallas, Texas.</p><p>The Video Competition asks students: &ldquo;<strong>What keeps your dream of graduating college alive?&rdquo;</strong> and encourages students at participating Achieving the Dream Colleges to submit <strong>informal videos</strong> that tell of personal challenges, inspiration, and connection to the programs offered to support graduation goals.</p>','','filtered_html');
