INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1724,3623,'und',0,'<p>The support of student success interventions from the top levels of institutional leadership is absolutely critical to the success of those interventions. While college presidents and other key administrators may verbalize their support of such interventions, only their genuine advocacy for these efforts will translate into positive outcomes. But what does committed leadership really look like? What can college administrators do to demonstrate that they truly value student success and to support the evolution of a culture of evidence on their campuses? This workshop will identify specific ways that top administrators at two Texas ATD Leader Colleges have supported ATD at their institutions with tips on: establishing effective communication between the top levels of leadership and those implementing the interventions; benefits of active participation in meetings with the ATD Coaches and the ATD Strategy Institutes; ways to participate in the interventions themselves; and the importance of active commitment to broad campus engagement and the institutionalization of student success interventions. The net result of this kind of active administrative leadership is the development of a comprehensive student success agenda at each institution.</p><ul><li>Larry Durrence, Interim College President, College of the Mainland, TX</li><li>Pam Millsap, Department Chair, Social and Behavioral Sciences, College of the Mainland, TX</li><li>Millecent Valek, President, Brazosport College, TX</li><li>Lynda Villanueva, Associate Dean of Instruction, Brazosport College, TX, and Achieving the Dream Data Coach</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1725,3624,'und',0,'<p>Representatives from the five Ohio ATD schools, in collaboration with the Ohio Association of Community Colleges, formed a planning team to share the ATD principles, data, promising practices, etc. with the other 18 community colleges in Ohio. Ohio community college faculty, staff, and administrators have been invited to statewide and regional sessions to leverage the lessons learned at Ohio&rsquo;s five ATD Institutions, which are all ATD Leader Colleges. Ohio ATD college representatives will share their model for expanding the student success conversation across the state and will facilitate mock regional workshops, similar to workshops conducted across Ohio in summer 2011.</p><ul><li>Jennifer Spielvogel, Vice President, Planning and Institutional Effectiveness, Cuyahoga Community College, OH</li><li>Christina Wanat, Director of DEI, Eastern Gateway Community College, OH</li><li>Tom Prendergast, Director, Institutional Research and Grants, North Central State College, OH</li><li>Lori Zakel, Chair, Communications Arts, Sinclair Community College, OH</li><li>Chad Brown, Vice President, Academic Services and Workforce Development, Zane State College, OH</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
