INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','news',0,1791,3720,'und',0,'<p>Oakland Community College student MiVida Burrus of Troy was the keynote speaker for the opening dinner at the Achieving the Dream Annual Meeting on Student Success recently held in Dallas, Texas.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1792,3721,'und',0,'<p>Two colleges began at different points &ndash; one with an existing strategic plan and the other needing to develop a plan. Both relied on metrics to inform top leadership and faculty and staff. One received a mandate from its board, the other with a mandate and direction from top administration. Both colleges used a Balanced Scorecard, for different reasons. One believed it was integral to conveying ends metrics and accountability for results in the strategic plan. The<br />other needed a way to convey information on a holistic basis; i.e., breaking down information silos. For both, the ATD student success metrics were front and center. Workshop participants will learn about: (1) a framework for translating ends policies into a strategic plan with metrics, including engagin faculty and staff in their development; (2) how the ATD focus on student success significantly impacted the overall institutional ends metrics and the strategic plans; (3)<br />how balanced scorecards and a metrics-informed strategy execution process can help break down institutional silos; and (4) how the colleges understood and dealt with organizational and technical challenges. Handouts will include planning process overviews, strategy maps, and scorecards.</p><ul><li>Don Plotts, President, North Central State College, OH</li><li>Tom Prendergast, Director of Institutional Research, North Central State College, OH</li><li>David Buchdahl, Director of Institutional Research and Planning, Community College of Vermont, VT</li><li>Deborah Stewart, Dean of Students, Community College of Vermont, VT</li><li>Joyce Judy, President, Community College of Vermont, VT</li><li>Bruce McComb, Organizational Effectiveness Consultants, OH and Achieving the Dream Data Coach</li><li>Jan Lyddon, Achieving the Dream Data Coach, OH</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1795,3724,'und',0,'<p>Zane State College joined Achieving the Dream in 2005, focusing its efforts on understanding the world-view and decision-making framework of students in poverty, along with placing primary emphasis on early engagement of students. Initial data analysis led to the creation of an integrated first-year experience, expanded advising efforts based upon a &ldquo;personal touch&rdquo; philosophy, and early identification of at-risk students. These efforts coincided with the creation of a new strategic plan, becoming an AQIP institution through the Higher Learning Commission, and participation in the Foundations of Excellence process, thus necessitating a concentrated effort to create a systematic plan for integrating the college&rsquo;s work. Applying ATD principles (committed leadership, broad engagement, use of evidence, and systematic institutional improvement), Zane State documented significant gains in student persistence, developmental education completion, and retention of high-risk students. Through the Developmental Education Initiative the college expanded work on developmental education acceleration and college-level and developmental course linkages. Presenters will share successes and challenges they faced in their efforts to create a data-informed culture focused on student success and bringing successful initiatives to scale &mdash; all while experiencing record<br />enrollment growth.</p><p>Moderator: Lynn Barnett, Consultant, Achieving the Dream, American Association of Community Colleges, DC</p><p>Panelists:</p><ul><li>Paul R. Brown, President, Zane State College, OH</li><li>Chad M. Brown, Vice President for Academic Services and Workforce Development, Zane State College, OH</li><li>Becky Ament, Associate Dean for Developmental Education and the First-Year Experience, Zane State College, OH</li><li>Stacie Mahaffey, Director, Student Success Center, Zane State College, OH</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1796,3725,'und',0,'<p>Kapi&rsquo;olani Community College recently implemented a comprehensive redesign of professional development to better engage faculty in their own learning and transform attitudes towards sustained professional learning. This initiative, C4ward: Collaborative Circles for Creative Change, has engaged greater numbers of faculty in organic, faculty-driven, decentralized experiences in authentic high-impact learning modeled on principles of apprenticeship, andragogy, and communities of practice. This interactive workshop invites participants to consider whether their college&rsquo;s professional development programs are effective in supporting faculty learning and engagement. Participants will learn and practice unique facilitation techniques for transforming professional development on their own campuses. The process of designing, piloting, implementing, and assessing the C4ward initiative will be shared, along with faculty comments about the 20 different C4wards currently running. One C4ward, the Vanguard Faculty Initiative, will be described in detail. The Vanguard C4ward addressed transferlevel course redesign for the college&rsquo;s most notorious &ldquo;gatekeeper&rdquo; courses and reduced faculty reluctance to redesign their courses. Participants will leave with skills, models, and inspiration to improve faculty learning and engagement on their own campuses.</p><ul><li>Charles Sasaki, Dean of Arts and Sciences, Kapi&rsquo;olani Community College, HI</li><li>Krista Hiser, Associate Professor/Developmental Composition, Kapi&rsquo;olani Community College, HI</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1797,3726,'und',0,'<p>The Achieving the Dream database is the largest student-level longitudinal database in the country and provides a wealth of information about students&lsquo; progressions through their academic careers. For six years, Data Notes authors have analyzed the Achieving the Dream database, beginning with the 2002 student cohorts and tracking the earliest students for up to eight years. This publication has highlighted interesting and notable findings surrounding ATD goals to increase student success and outcomes. This workshop will focus on some of the thought-provoking findings and provide the opportunity for colleges to participate in an open dialogue regarding the data, the findings, and their implications. Presenters will also highlight analytical lessons learned from working with the ATD database and how to optimize the analytical capability of the data.</p><ul><li>Suzanne Clery, Achieving the Dream Project Manager, JBL Associates, MD</li><li>Amy Topper, Achieving the Dream Data Coordinator, JBL Associates, MD</li><li>Elif Bor, Achieving the Dream Data Coordinator, JBL Associates, MD</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1798,3727,'und',0,'<p>In this workshop administrators and faculty will learn how the Community College of Baltimore County has reframed and implemented the way it approaches preparing students for college success. The creation of a mandatory one-credit course to help prepare all students academically and socially for the challenges of college is a unique and scalable approach touching a significant majority of CCBC students. Participants will hear about the collaborative development process, the creation of the financial literacy component, the implementation of special sections for African-American males, and the development of customized health professions sections. Challenges, solutions, and outcomes will be presented.</p><ul><li>Susan Delker, Department Chair of Academic Development, The Community College of Baltimore County, MD</li><li>Sonya Caesar, Coordinator of Developmental Education, The Community College of Baltimore County, MD</li><li>Estelle Young, Director of Student Success Support for the School of Health Professions, The Community College of Baltimore County, MD</li><li>Mark McColloch, Vice President for Instruction, The Community College of Baltimore County, MD</li><li>Mark Williams, Director of Counseling and Career Development Services, The Community College of Baltimore County, MD</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1805,3737,'und',0,'<p>This workshop will present findings from the Community College Research Center&rsquo;s implementation research conducted at the six Round 3 Washington State colleges. Presenters will share data on the colleges&lsquo;progress after five years of participation in ATD and will highlight major successes and challenges of implementing the five-step process of institutional reform. The session will also include information from Washington college practitioners about strategies to overcome challenges and limitations during the reform process. Recommendations for the continuous improvement of ATD will also be reviewed.</p><ul><li>John Wachen, Senior Research Assistant, Community College Research Center, NY</li><li>Davis Jenkins, Senior Research Associate, Community College Research Center, NY, and Achieving the Dream Data Coach</li><li>Oscar Cerna, Research Associate, MDRC, CA</li><li>Tomas Ybarra, Vice President for Instruction and Student Services, Yakima Valley Community College, WA</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1807,3739,'und',0,'<p>Delta College and Montcalm Community College (MCC) created initiatives to educate each college about Achieving the Dream and its principles. Delta College will discuss how and why they created an informative video regarding ATD at the college. They will discuss the timeline for the video&rsquo;s creation and who was involved in its production. Delta will address how the video has been used to engage faculty and to inspire discussions within the college community. Panelists will discuss how and why MCC held a school-year kick-off event that drove home the message of Achieving the Dream in a fun and energetic way by creating a football-style game that addressed obstacles students typically face. Details will be provided on how the event worked, and participants will take part in a discussion about what has worked at other campuses. Lauren Lewis will provide information about tools and resources that are available for ATD Colleges use to support their communications efforts. Participants will leave with a full understanding of the resources available for their use and will be able to provide feedback on other ways in which ATD could help them in their communications efforts.</p><ul><li>David Baskind, Associate Professor of Psychology, Delta College, MI</li><li>Brigit Dyer, Director of Retention, Delta College, MI</li><li>Robert Ferrentino, President, Montcalm Community College, MI</li><li>Robert Spohr, Vice President for Academic Affairs, Montcalm Community College, MI</li><li>Lauren Lewis, Assistant Director of Communications, Achieving the Dream, MD</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1808,3740,'und',0,'<p>Durham Technical Community College is a Round One Achieving the Dream Institution and leadership college. Since 2004, the college has deliberately developed one-credit-hour college success course that supports the needs of our students; systematically trained faculty, staff, and administrators to teach the course; and strategically required the course for new college students. In this session, workshop participants will engage in critical conversations around two issues related to designing a college success course for new students: faculty engagement and full-scale implementation. Specifically, participants will evaluate strategies for faculty engagement and<br />training; they will also examine their own colleges&rsquo; commitment to full-scale implementation and identify potential loopholes.</p><ul><li>Gabby McCutchen, Chair/Instructor, First Year Experience, Durham Technical Community College, NC</li><li>Christine Kelly-Kleese, Dean and Department Head, Student Engagement and Transitions, Durham Technical Community College, NC</li><li>Tom Jaynes, Executive Dean, Student Development and Support, Durham Technical Community College, NC</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','news',0,1813,3745,'und',0,'<p>Hello, good neighbors! We have some cool updates to share with you on some of the activities we reported on in last week&rsquo;s&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.thegoodneighborhood.com/2012/02/28/you-and-whosday-achieving-the-dream-in-dallas-launching-new-site-during-sxsw-in-austin/\" target=\"_blank\">post</a>&nbsp;from Dallas.</p><p>Last week&rsquo;s trip to the Lone Star State was very successful for You and Who. We had a great time at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://achievingthedream.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Achieving the Dream</a>&lsquo;s national conference, where we were able to interact with thousands of educators across the country. It was inspiring, to say the least, to learn how this organization is encouraging community colleges everywhere to provide students, particularly low-income and minority students, with the tools, support, and encouragement they need to stay in school and earn a college certificate or degree.</p>','','filtered_html');
