INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1847,3783,'und',0,'<p>Oakland Community College&rsquo;s key themes have been the integration and alignment of Achieving the Dream planning and action with ongoing processes. The Student Success Survey builds on that theme by polling students about potential barriers to success and categorizing them as dispositional, institutional, or situational barriers. The college&rsquo;s teams used existing student feedback surveys, results of one-on-one student interviews, and findings from focus groups to develop the content, along with dissertation research from OCC&rsquo;s ATD leader to align the perceived barriers into categories. The primary strategy teams are using feedback from the survey as a learning tool, and using survey results and feedback to adapt the survey as needed. Learn how to turn barriers into pathways to success. How would you apply this knowledge to your own college? To your school&rsquo;s policies?</p><ul><li>Nancy Showers, Director of Institutional Research, Oakland Community College, MI and Achieving the Dream Data Coach</li><li>Henry Tanaka, Dean of Academic and Student Services, Oakland Community College, MI</li><li>Suba Subbarao, English Faculty, Oakland Community College, MI</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1848,3825,'und',0,'<p>Student success courses are frequently cited as effective vehicles for enhancing the retention of college students from semester-to-semester and from year-to-year. Many Achieving the Dream Institutions have chosen to implement such courses as key interventions on their campuses. These courses can be structured in many different ways, but one may wonder: How can different student success course models from various colleges be successful? What characteristics should every student success course have in order to ensure it is effective? Brazosport College and College of the Mainland implemented two contrasting, yet successful, student success course models for increasing indices of student success. Come learn about the struggles and successes of these two Texas Leader Colleges and how they utilized the ATD process of institutional improvement to develop learning atmospheres that are strategically designed to lead to positive changes in the college classroom and beyond. Be prepared to share experiences with the development and implementation of your own student success course.</p><ul><li>Lynda Villanueva, Associate Dean of Instruction, Brazosport College, TX and Achieving the Dream Data Coach</li><li>Pam Millsap, Department Chair, Social and Behavioral Sciences, College of the Mainland, TX</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1849,3785,'und',0,'<p>Why should you care about your students&rsquo; sex lives? Because 61% of women who have children while enrolled in community colleges drop out and do not return. Learn from colleges involved in AACC&rsquo;s national initiative, Make It Personal: College Completion, about how they are working to improve retention and completion by using curricular interventions to help students avoid unplanned pregnancy and complete their college goals. Presenters will share up-to-the-minute national survey data on student retention, knowledge, attitudes, and behavioral intent. Attendees will learn why and how pregnancy planning and prevention can affect student retention/persistence; how service learning can be an effective intervention; challenges involved in implementing the interventions and how to overcome them; and how to use replicable curricular materials and innovative online resources at their own institutions.</p><ul><li>Mike Flores, Vice President for Student Affairs, Palo Alto College, TX and Achieving the Dream Data Coach</li><li>Mary Prentice, Associate Professor, Educational Management and Development, New Mexico State University</li><li>Gail Robinson, Director of Service Learning, American Association of Community Colleges, DC</li><li>Chelsey Storin, Manager, Policy and Programs, National Campaign to Prevent Teen and Unplanned Pregnancy, DC</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
