INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1857,3794,'und',0,'<p>An $18 million effort led by MDC and funded by the Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation and Lumina Foundation, the Developmental Education Initiative (DEI) is scaling up innovations piloted in Achieving the Dream Colleges and States. Fifteen DEI colleges and six DEI states are scaling up policies and practices that can generate improvements for more developmental education students. Lessons learned from DEI are already making their way through the ATD Network and beyond. The workshop will provide an introduction to DEI and More to Most, a new guidebook for scaling up effective practices at community colleges that features the SCALERS model, seven organizational capacities that institutions can deploy to successfully expand programs. Participants will learn how Guilford Technical Community College has applied these principles to DEI work on its campus, as well as how Jackson Community College has implemented the More to Most process to design a scaling plan for ATD interventions.</p><p><strong>Moderator:</strong> Holly Zanville, Program Director, Lumina Foundation, IN</p><p><strong>Panelists:</strong></p><ul><li>Abby Parcell, DEI Program Manager, MDC, NC</li><li>Ginger Miller, DEI Grant Coordinator, Guilford Technical Community College, NC</li><li>Charlotte Finnegan, Dean, Foundation Studies and Student Support, Jackson Community College, MI</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1858,3796,'und',0,'<p>While many studies have focused on understanding the &ldquo;best practices&rdquo; for improving developmental education, it is only fairly recently that research has begun to take a more rigorous approach. This session highlights promising strategies and practices in developmental education instruction learned from a collection of studies conducted at various Achieving the Dream Colleges. The session will spotlight: (1) promising approaches for revising the structure, curriculum, and delivery of developmental education based on a review of rigorous research; (2) how supplemental instruction and peer mentor programs can be used to support the academic success of developmental math and first-year students; and (3) key findings on the effectiveness of summer bridge programs, learning communities, and success courses in improving developmental education students&rsquo; achievement.</p><p><strong>Moderator:</strong> Nahir Torres, Program Officer, The Boston Foundation, MA</p><p><strong>Panelists:</strong></p><ul><li>Elizabeth Zachry Rutschow, Research Associate, MDRC, CA</li><li>Oscar Cerna, Research Associate, MDRC, CA</li><li>Evan Weissman, Research Associate, MDRC, CA</li><li>Heather Wathington, Achieving the Dream Data Coach, VA</li><li>Bill Heineman, Vice President of Academic Affairs, Northern Essex Community College, PA</li><li>Charles Cook, Vice President of Instruction, Houston Community College, TX</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','person',0,1878,3819,'und',0,'<p><em>Managing Principal for the McPhail Group LLC and Emerita Professor and Founder of CCLDP at Morgan State University</em></p><p>Christine McPhail is the Managing Principal for the McPhail Group LLC, a higher education consulting firm; Emerita Professor of higher education and founder of the Community College Leadership Doctoral Program at Morgan State University, and a Coach for Achieving the Dream. She was recently appointed to serve on the Gates Foundation&rsquo;s Completion by Design National Advisory Committee.</p><p>Dr. McPhail is the recipient of the 2010 AACC National Leadership Award and the 2008 League of Innovation&lsquo;s Terry O&rsquo;Banion Leadership Award. She formerly served as the President and Chief Instructional Officer at Cypress College in southern California. She serves on the Advisory Council for the Community College Survey of Student Engagement (CCSSE) and the National Center for Postsecondary Research (NCPR) at the Community College Research Center (CCRC) ; and Coach, Achieving the Dream. She recently served on the Board of Directors for the American Association of Community Colleges (AACC) and the Council for the Study of Community Colleges (CSCC). McPhail formerly served as the Affirmative Action Officer, Division J, American Education Research Association (AERA) and on the Editorial Board for the Community College Journal of Research and Practice.</p><p>She is the Editor for one of AACC&rsquo;s best-selling publications, Establishing and Sustaining Learning Centered Community Colleges. She was the featured international keynote speaker at the Guardian Further Education and Skills Summit 2007 in the United Kingdom. Her research interests lie in the intersection of three fields of higher education: leadership, governance, and learning.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1880,3826,'und',0,'<p>Valencia College employs many proven strategies to increase the success of all students, but too often first-year students experience their coursework as isolated learning opportunities. To increase the likelihood that developmental education students will have a more fully-integrated experience and be successful in transferring academic skills and behaviors across disciplines and into all aspects of their lives, Valencia created REACH, a new cohort-based learning community for students who were placed in developmental education courses in reading, writing, and mathematics. Progressing as a cohort through a program that begins with three developmental courses and ends with 21college-level credits, they experience their first year under the direction of a faculty team that collaborates intensively to create a richly-integrated curriculum enhanced with a co-curricular component. Workshop participants will be able to walk through the processes used in the creation and implementation of this learning community, including the data which informed decisions. Data on REACH&rsquo;s first term will be shared. Participants will brainstorm potential adaptations of this learning community at their institutions, raise issues of potential challenges, and get feedback on possible solutions.</p><ul><li>Nicholas Bekas, Director, Developmental Education Initiative, Valencia College, FL</li><li>Al Groccia, Professor of Mathematics, Valencia College, FL</li><li>Marilyn Curall, Professor of English, Valencia College, FL</li><li>Summer Trazzera, Professor of Reading, Valencia College, FL</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1881,3827,'und',0,'<p>The buy-in of a critical mass of faculty and staff is necessary for widespread and lasting institutional change. How can we encourage faculty and staff inquiry, research, and exploration of new teaching and learning pedagogies? How can the establishment of learning communities across the curriculum, with integrated student services, promote student success? And how can we move from the implementation of a best practice to a fundamental shift in institutional policy and practice? A faculty/staff-driven approach to change, supported by a robust professional development program, helped create a more successful learning environment for students at Bunker Hill Community College. Participants will engage in a discussion on activities that promote collaborations across academic departments, and partnerships between faculty and student services staff. They will be provided with a tool that they can use to construct a similar model that could be replicated on their campus. Participants will come away with ideas for creative funding solutions.</p><ul><li>Janice Bonanno, Associate Vice President, Student Services, Bunker Hill Community College, MA</li><li>David Leavitt, Director of Institutional Research, Bunker Hill Community College, MA</li><li>Jesse Thompson, Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer, Bunker Hill Community College, MA</li><li>James Canniff, Vice President of Academic Affairs and Student Services, Bunker Hill Community College, MA</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','news',0,1888,3845,'und',0,'<p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(153, 153, 153); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \">Thursday, March 15, 2012</span></p><div class=\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\" style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; font-size: 12px; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; \"><div class=\"field-items\" style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \"><div class=\"field-item even\" property=\"content:encoded\" style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \"><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \">Phi Theta Kappa&rsquo;s students, staff and C4 initiative shared in the spotlight recently at the annual Achieving the Dream conference held in Dallas, Texas.</p><div class=\"caption_photo right\" style=\"margin-bottom: 15px; margin-left: 15px; padding-top: 8px; padding-right: 8px; padding-bottom: 8px; padding-left: 8px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: rgb(232, 232, 232); float: right; border-top-left-radius: 6px; border-top-right-radius: 6px; border-bottom-right-radius: 6px; border-bottom-left-radius: 6px; text-align: center; \"><br /><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; font-size: 11px; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; width: 300px; color: rgb(119, 119, 119); \"><a class=\"colorbox colorbox-insert-image init-colorbox-processed-processed cboxElement\" href=\"http://www.ptk.org/sites/default/files/Dream%20PTK%203.JPG\" rel=\"gallery-all\" style=\"background-color: transparent; font-size: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; color: rgb(0, 153, 255); text-decoration: underline; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgb(255, 94, 153); \" title=\"C4 Presenters Jeong Lee and Hanh Nguyen of North Lake College, Irving, Texas.\"><img alt=\"Phi Theta Kappa members Jeong Lee and Hanh Nguyen of North Lake College, TX.\" src=\"http://www.ptk.org/?q=sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/Dream%20PTK%203.JPG\" style=\"margin-bottom: 10px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \" title=\"C4 Presenters Jeong Lee and Hanh Nguyen of North Lake College, Irving, Texas.\" typeof=\"foaf:Image\" /></a></p><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; font-size: 11px; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; width: 300px; color: rgb(119, 119, 119); \"><span style=\"font-size: 12px; \">Members Jeong Lee and Hanh Nguyen of&nbsp;</span>the North Lake College Phi Theta Kappa Chapter, Irving, Texas</p></div><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \">Phi Theta Kappa&#39;s Executive Director Dr. Rod Risley and Dean of Service Learning Jennifer Stanford were joined by three of the Society&#39;s Texas chapters in sharing strategies for making college completion a top priority for community college students at a pre-conference event sponsored by Achieving the Dream.&nbsp;</p><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \">Phi Theta Kappa presenters included Jeong Lee and Hanh Nguyen of North Lake College in Irving, Texas; Michael Navarro of Brookhaven College in Farmers Branch, Texas; and alumnus Candace Eldridge of Tarrant County College-Trinity River, who now serves as a chapter advisor.</p><div class=\"caption_photo right\" style=\"margin-bottom: 15px; margin-left: 15px; padding-top: 8px; padding-right: 8px; padding-bottom: 8px; padding-left: 8px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: rgb(232, 232, 232); float: right; border-top-left-radius: 6px; border-top-right-radius: 6px; border-bottom-right-radius: 6px; border-bottom-left-radius: 6px; text-align: center; \"><a class=\"colorbox colorbox-insert-image init-colorbox-processed-processed cboxElement\" href=\"http://www.ptk.org/sites/default/files/DREAM%20PTK%202.JPG\" rel=\"gallery-all\" style=\"background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 153, 255); -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgb(255, 94, 153); \" title=\"C4 Presenter Michael Navarro, Brookhaven College Chapter, TX.\"><img alt=\"Phi Theta Kappa member Michael Navarro of Brookhaven College, Farmers Branch,TX.\" src=\"http://www.ptk.org/?q=sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/DREAM%20PTK%202.JPG\" style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; margin-bottom: 10px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \" title=\"C4 Presenter Michael Navarro, Brookhaven College Chapter, TX.\" typeof=\"foaf:Image\" /></a><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; font-size: 11px; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; width: 300px; color: rgb(119, 119, 119); \">C4 Presenter Michael Navarro, Brookhaven College Chapter</p></div><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \">Stanford provided background on Phi Theta Kappa&rsquo;s partnership with other community college organizations and its prominent role in establishing the Community College Completion Corps website and resource materials to help the Society&rsquo;s 1,280 chapters spread the word on the importance of college completion. She also discussed one of Phi Theta Kappa&rsquo;s student development resources, the Five Star Competitive Edge professional development plan, which helps members strengthen their marketable skills to be more competitive for scholarships, transferring, and job placement.</p><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \">Dr. Risley addressed Phi Theta Kappa&rsquo;s CollegeFish.org transfer planning and scholarship search website that recently received a nearly $3 million grant from the Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation to boost college completion and transfer rates.</p><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \">MiVada Burris, a member of Phi Theta Kappa at Oakland Community College in Michigan, served as the keynote speaker during Tuesday&rsquo;s Plenary Session. View her speech online at<a href=\"http://achievingthedream.org/dream2012/tuesday_highlights\" style=\"background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 153, 255); -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgb(255, 94, 153); \">http://achievingthedream.org/dream2012/tuesday_highlights</a>.</p><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \">Mia Ramos, who served as 2005-2006 Division I International Vice President for Phi Theta Kappa, was recently named Assistant Director of Programs for New Colleges for Achieving the Dream, Inc. Achieving the Dream is a national reform network dedicated to community college student success and completion, focused primarily on helping low-income students and students of color complete their education and obtain market-valued credentials.</p><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \"><span style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \">&quot;The student voice is such an important part of our efforts at Achieving the Dream; they are the reason we do what we do,&quot; Ramos said. &quot;It was truly inspiring to hear of the amazing work of Phi Theta Kappa students engaged in the C4 College Completion Initiative and of their&nbsp;commitment&nbsp;to not only their individual success, but the success of all students on their campuses.&quot;</span></p><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \">Report your completion events at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.cccompletioncorps.org/ccccorps/ptk/got-commitment\" style=\"background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 153, 255); -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgb(255, 94, 153); \">http://www.cccompletioncorps.org/ccccorps/ptk/got-commitment&nbsp;</a>and be featured on the Community College Completion Corps website.</p><p style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 12px; border-style: initial; border-color: initial; outline-width: 0px; outline-style: initial; outline-color: initial; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; \">Downloadable C4 toolkit materials to plan your event are available online at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.cccompletioncorps.org/ptk\" style=\"background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 153, 255); -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgb(255, 94, 153); \">http://www.cccompletioncorps.org/ptk.</a></p></div></div></div><p>&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','page',0,1897,3857,'und',0,'<p>All Achieving the Dream Institutions are required to submit a draft and final implementation proposal narrative (including a work plan), a budget, and an updated contacts list at the end of their planning year.</p><p>These proposal guidelines provide a framework for organizing qualitative and quantitative data and creating a four-year implementation plan. While colleges commit to three years of implementation, we believe all colleges will need at least four years to effectively implement policy changes and new practices. This implementation will require financial support. Therefore, we also ask all colleges to prepare four-year rather than three-year implementation plans and budgets.</p><p>Second-year participation in Achieving the Dream is contingent on receipt of an acceptable implementation proposal.</p><p><em>**Guidelines and instructions on how to submit your Implementation Proposal will be provided on this page in Spring 2013.**</em></p><p>We invite you to review the 2012 guidelines as a reference, but please know that these documents are likely to change for 2013:</p><p><a href=\"http://www.achievingthedream.org/sites/default/files/ATD%20Implementation%20Proposal%20Guidelines.doc\" title=\"Implementation Proposal Guidelines\">Implementation Proposal Guidelines</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.achievingthedream.org/sites/default/files/ATD%20Implementation%20Proposal%20Budget%20Template.xls\" title=\"Budget Template\">Budget Template</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.achievingthedream.org/sites/default/files/ATD%20College%20Contact%20Information%20Template%20%282%29.xls\" title=\"Contact Information Template\">Contact Information Template</a></p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','resource',0,1905,3867,'und',0,'<p>&nbsp;</p><div>Community colleges play a vital role in advancing&nbsp;educational and economic opportunity for many&nbsp;Americans, especially low-income students and&nbsp;students of color. Without these institutions, our&nbsp;higher education system would be inaccessible to&nbsp;a large portion of our citizenry. Today, America is&nbsp;counting on community colleges to help students,&nbsp;regardless of background and level of preparation,&nbsp;obtain a credential or degree and put them on the&nbsp;path to economic security; community colleges are&nbsp;spending more time in the spotlight &mdash; and facing&nbsp;increased scrutiny &mdash; given the current status of the&nbsp;economy, of national college completion rates, and&nbsp;an increasing mismatch between available jobs and&nbsp;the skills of those available to work. Colleges across&nbsp;the country are responding in innovative ways, but&nbsp;sustaining the services, instruction, and training to&nbsp;meet these challenges will require colleges to move&nbsp;beyond small programs, no matter how successful.&nbsp;We&rsquo;re not just asking community colleges to soothe&nbsp;some of our toughest educational and economic&nbsp;woes, we&rsquo;re asking them to do it &ldquo;at scale.&rdquo;</div>','','filtered_html');
