INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','news',0,3416,7759,'und',0,'<div class=\"entry-content\"><p>For Oregon&rsquo;s economy to thrive, higher education must change.</p><p>That may sound surprising coming from a college president. But many are starting to question the value of college education versus taxpayer and student dollars spent. The questions are worth asking, and smart colleges will respond with answers and action.</p><p>Earlier this month, 850 people graduated with 996 degrees and certificates from Linn-Benton Community College. I am confident they will improve both their own lives and the quality of life in our communities.</p><p>But a recent report card for higher education issued by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce gave Oregon community colleges an &ldquo;F&rdquo; for the amount of money spent per degree earned.</p><p>The measurements had their flaws. The Chamber used a model developed for four-year universities that doesn&rsquo;t consider the number of students in non-degree programs such as adult basic education, GED and community education. Many argue that the &ldquo;IPEDs&rdquo; model is no longer an accurate measure even for four-year universities.</p><p>However, our own data are enough for us to know we&rsquo;re not earning an &ldquo;A.&rdquo; LBCC&rsquo;s &ldquo;success rate&rdquo; is 34 percent (12 percent of our students earn degrees or certificates and another 22 percent transfer to four-year colleges and universities).</p><p>We can and must do better to help more of our citizens finish what they start at LBCC.</p><p>The Oregon Education Investment Board&rsquo;s goals and achievement compacts are a good start. They challenge the education system to ensure 40 percent of adults have a bachelor&rsquo;s degree, 40 percent have a two-year degree or job-ready certificate, and 20 percent have at least a high school diploma or the equivalent by 2025.</p><p>That means LBCC must increase the number of people earning degrees or certificates from 850 to 1,350 per year. Despite significant cuts in state funding over the past three years, our first moves must be to do new and better things with the resources we have.</p><p>Already we are discussing new educational design that will fit a broader array of learning styles and life circumstances. We hope to have more balance of online and face-to-face instruction. We are considering options that are not time-based. Some people can quickly master concepts and competencies in some subject areas. They should not be held back. Others need more time. They should not be dubbed failures because of that.</p><p>By fall, LBCC will launch new initiatives to better prepare students to succeed. From point of first contact through their enrollment, we will better prepare people to make important choices, and establish key relationships inside LBCC. Research indicates these are keys to college success and completion.</p><p>LBCC was also selected this year to join the national Achieving the Dream network of community colleges. This resource will help us better document what processes are helping and hindering our students to complete in the most efficient way.</p><p>And we continue to work closely with local partners in industry to ensure our programs are aligned with the kind of skilled workers they need.</p><p>We know we are changing lives for the better every day. We hear stories from our alumni that confirm this. But we also know if we do not do more, our economy and our community will not thrive.</p><p>I&rsquo;m confident LBCC will meet this challenge.</p><p><em>Greg Hamann is the president of Linn-Benton Community College.</em></p></div><p>&nbsp;</p>','','filtered_html');
