INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','news',0,3449,7867,'und',0,'<p><img alt=\"\" class=\"image-inline_photo_float_right\" src=\"http://www.achievingthedream.org/sites/default/files/styles/inline_photo_float_right/public/images/Susie_Student_Spotlight.jpg\" title=\"\" />CLEVELAND, Ohio -- It was January 2010, and Susie Porter was ready to give up.</p><p>The economy had gotten so bad that regulars at her restaurant were coming in one day a week instead of three or four.</p><p>Her 26-year-old daughter had taken a fall and fractured her neck. <em>Pick up your baby and you could end up paralyzed,</em> her doctor told her.</p><p>That&#39;s why Porter was standing in the steamy kitchen of the Town Fryer at the Agora -- stirring pots of gumbo and red beans and rice -- with a 1-year-old on her hip.</p><p>She was 52 and single, had no health insurance and her 10-year-old Jeep was emptying her wallet faster than a thief.</p><p>If all that wasn&#39;t worrying her, her daughter&#39;s health was. What if Ali didn&#39;t recover? How could Porter support her and her baby, for years, on the little money she was bringing in?</p><p><em>This is insane,</em> Porter told herself. <em>I can&#39;t live like this. I&#39;ve got to do something.</em></p><p>She has.</p><p>In a few weeks, Susie Porter leaves for upstate New York to begin her junior year of college on a full scholarship -- room and board included -- at an Ivy League research university, Cornell.</p><p>&quot;If you have a dream, if you <em>had</em> a dream, it&#39;s never too late to go for it,&quot; Porter says.</p><p>&quot;My God, I&#39;m 54 years old, and I&#39;m going off to college.&quot;</p><p>It all happened because a friend stopped by the restaurant, as he did every morning, and told her he was going back to school, that he&#39;d gotten enough financial aid to make it work.</p><p>&quot;You can get grants and you can get loans and you&#39;ll be OK,&quot; he told Porter on that cold January morning, 21/2 years ago.</p><p>&quot;I&#39;ll show you how.&quot;</p><p>Porter sat down next to him, right there in the restaurant with her granddaughter on her lap, and applied to <a href=\"http://www.csuohio.edu/\">Cleveland State University</a>.</p><p>Her next piece of good fortune was getting an adviser who explained CSU&#39;s partnership program with <a href=\"http://www.tri-c.edu/Pages/default.aspx\">Cuyahoga Community College</a>, which allowed Porter to take less expensive Tri-C courses that counted toward a CSU<strong> </strong>degree.</p><p>Porter jumped on that.</p><p>But even with the lower tuition, she needed grants and loans to make it.</p><p>The first semester, she enrolled in three online classes, taking nine credit hours, so she could continue to take care of her daughter and granddaughter and because she was nervous about starting college in her 50s.</p><p>&quot;It had been 34 years since I had been in high school,&quot; she says, &quot;and I was wondering if I could still learn.&quot;</p><p>She got straight A&#39;s.</p><p>And she kept at it, choosing urban affairs as her major.</p><p>Her grades were good enough to get her into the honors program as well as induction into <a href=\"http://www.ptk.org/?destination=node\">Phi Theta Kappa</a>, the academic honor society for two-year colleges. She was accepted into the <a href=\"http://www.tri-c.edu/programs/honors/Pages/RobertLLewisAcademyofScholars.aspx\">Robert L. Lewis Academy of Scholars</a>, too.</p><p>Scholarship money started coming in after that.</p><p>Then, in September 2011, she opened the mailbox and pulled out a letter from Cornell, inviting her to apply to its School of Industrial and Labor Relations. It was a perfect fit. She&#39;d always been interested in workers&#39; rights and social justice.</p><p>&quot;Yeah, right,&quot; Porter said when she&#39;d finished reading. And she laughs a soft, sweet laugh that hints at her Texas and Louisiana roots.</p><p>With her daughter healed and the restaurant closed, she went ahead and called the admissions office, just as the letter suggested.</p><p>The following month, she made the 5 1/2-hour drive to Ithaca, N.Y.,<strong> </strong>to check out the campus.</p><p>She was sold.</p><p>&quot;It&#39;s huge,&quot; Porter says. &quot;But even in its enormity it feels like you are just absolutely enveloped in this nurturing environment. It feels like it just wraps itself around you.&quot;</p><p>In February, she sent in her application.</p><p>Weeks later, on a Friday night, she looked down at her cellphone and saw she&#39;d missed a call. She checked voicemail. Ian Schachner, the associate director for admissions for the School of Industrial and Labor Relations, wanted to talk to her.</p><p><em>This can&#39;t be good, </em>Porter thought. <em>You get the fat envelope in the mail when you&#39;re accepted.</em></p><p>And she fretted all weekend.</p><p>When she called back on Monday, Schachner told her he didn&#39;t want her to wait for an answer any longer. Cornell wanted her.</p><p>&quot;When he hung up,&quot; Porter says, &quot;I cried like a baby.&quot;</p><p>Porter knew her acceptance meant she&#39;d get financial help, too, because of Cornell&#39;s policy of providing scholarships to students who can&#39;t afford tuition, room and board.</p><p>That letter came later.</p><p>The total value of the school&#39;s offer: $56,497 for just the first year.</p><p>Schachner says Porter is the kind of student Cornell searches for.</p><p>&quot;We talk a lot about diversity in education, and diversity is often spoken of as race or ethnicity,&quot; he said in a telephone interview. &quot;But it also means diversity in life experiences.</p><p>&quot;We love students who have been out there for a while -- people who can help the younger students realize, &#39;Hey, this is actually what goes on in organizations, this is how the world really works.&#39; &quot;</p><p>His message to other students: forget about the barriers you think are there.</p><p>&quot;There&#39;s an enormous number of fears that they have: &#39;I can&#39;t afford it, they&#39;d never take me, I wouldn&#39;t be able to do the work, I don&#39;t have the support,&#39; &quot;Schachner says.</p><p>&quot;The only thing that matches the number of fears they have is the actual support that exists to help them.&quot;</p><p>And that support, Porter says, is a gift she never would have received if not for the people who helped her along the way. And if not for Tri-C.</p><p>&quot;Ian told me that he had rarely seen a transfer student come in with as many transferable credits as I had,&quot; she says. &quot;That really says a lot for Tri-C.&quot;</p><p>And it means more students like her can get into schools like Cornell, Porter says. She&#39;s willing to help them do it. She&#39;s offering advice now on the blog she just created, <a href=\"http://susiep54.posterous.com/\">susiep54.posterous.com</a>.</p><p>&quot;If you work hard, there&#39;s money available to go to school,&quot; she says.</p><p>She wants to alert older students to hurdles besides money: that they need to dig up high school transcripts, for example, and find old immunization records.</p><p>&quot;It&#39;s funny how people put labels on people,&quot; Porter says, thinking back to everyone who knew her as &quot;The Fry Lady,&quot; the woman who deep-fried Twinkies and Oreos along with her famous chicken and baseball-sized servings of homemade macaroni and cheese at the Town Fryer restaurant she ran for years on Superior Avenue.</p><p>&quot;They can&#39;t get past people having more than one side to them.</p><p>&quot;What&#39;s even more interesting is that it&#39;s hard for people to realize that they have more than one side to themselves.&quot;</p><p>&quot;They think they&#39;re too old to go back to school.&quot;</p><p>Not Porter.</p><p>In August, she&#39;ll be in classrooms filled with 20-year-old college juniors. And in two years, she&#39;ll have her bachelor&#39;s degree -- and have figured out what she&#39;ll do next.</p><p>&quot;Law school is not out of the question,&quot; she says.</p><p>&quot;I&#39;ll be 56 and I&#39;ll be ready to take on the world.&quot;</p>','','filtered_html');
