INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','news',0,3923,9120,'und',0,'<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"7\" style=\"vertical-align:top;\"><tr><td width=\"80\" align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"><font style=\"font-size:85%;font-family:arial,sans-serif\"></font></td><td valign=\"top\" class=\"j\"><font style=\"font-size:85%;font-family:arial,sans-serif\"><br /><div style=\"padding-top:0.8em;\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\" /></div><div class=\"lh\"><a href=\"http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=t&amp;fd=R&amp;usg=AFQjCNERyDewfwYa6vfx4GKnC3WWm-VNVA&amp;url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/news/news/state-launches-new-strategy-to-help-transfer-stude/nSg5W/\"><b>State launches new strategy to help transfer students earn 2-year degrees</b></a><br /><font size=\"-1\"><b><font color=\"#6f6f6f\">Dayton Daily News</font></b></font><br /><font size=\"-1\">About 75 percent of the nearly 49,800 students who enrolled in Ohio&#39;s public universities after attending a community college transferred before receiving an associate degree, according to the <b>Lumina Foundation</b>, a national nonprofit committed to <b>...</b></font><br /><font size=\"-1\" class=\"p\"></font><br /><font class=\"p\" size=\"-1\"><a class=\"p\" href=\"http://news.google.com/news/more?ncl=d18wjg6e4bmA9FM&amp;ned=us\"><nobr><b>and more&nbsp;&raquo;</b></nobr></a></font></div></font></td></tr></table>',NULL,'filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','page',0,3924,9122,'und',0,'<p><a name=\"top\"></a>Pre-Meeting Workshops will be offered to participants on Tuesday, February 5, prior to the formal opening of DREAM 2013, Achieving the Dream&rsquo;s Annual Meeting on Student Success, that evening. All participants who would like to attend a Pre-Meeting Workshop must pre-register by January 22, 2013. As space for the workshops is limited, please register early to reserve your seat. You can pick up your Pre-Meeting Workshop tickets at the registration counter at the Hilton Anaheim. Fees for the Pre-Meeting Workshops cover catering, audio visual, workshop materials, and meeting room expenses.</p><ul><li><a href=\"#A\">Workshop A: Promoting Academic Success for Men of Color: Understanding Challenges, Seizing Opportunities</a></li><li><a href=\"#B\">Workshop B: Introduction to Carnegie&#39;s Networked Improvement Community on Developmental Math</a></li><li><a href=\"#C\">Workshop C: Bringing Learning Communities to Scale: From Some to More to Most</a></li><li><a href=\"#D\">Workshop D: Engaging Your Board for Student Success</a></li><li><a href=\"#E\">Workshop E: Using ATD Tools to Advance Equity and Reduce Achievement Gaps</a></li><li><a href=\"#F\">Workshop F: Orchestrating the Use of Data: Data Summits as the Launch</a></li><li><a href=\"#G\">Workshop G: Phi Theta Kappa/DREAMbassadors: A Student-Led Alliance for College Completion</a></li><li><a href=\"#H\">Workshop H: Introduction to Carnegie&#39;s Networked Improvement Community on Developmental Math</a></li><li><a href=\"#I\">Workshop I: Building a Successful Prior Learning Assessment (PLA) Program in Partnership</a></li><li><a href=\"#J\">Workshop J: Faculty Development: Keys to Scaling Up Acceleration in Developmental Writing</a></li></ul><h2><a name=\"A\"></a>Workshop A: Promoting Academic Success for Men of Color: Understanding Challenges, Seizing Opportunities</h2><p><strong>Tuesday, February 5, 9:00am - 12:00pm</strong></p><p>Advance Registration and Ticket Required: Fee &ndash; Complimentary<br />Continental breakfast (8 &ndash; 9 AM) included for workshop attendees&nbsp;</p><p>Analysis of data on the engagement, progress, and success of Latinos and African American men in community colleges often leads to more questions than answers. Workshop participants will briefly review recent findings from student engagement surveys, cohort tracking, and focus groups. Small group discussions will focus on key questions that emerge from the findings, including: <em>What are our shared understandings about the ways that African American men and Latinos establish personal connections and a sense of belonging in their community colleges? How can colleges build bridges from students&#39; successful out-of-class engagement to effective academic engagement? What is being learned about the impacts of targeting interventions in support of particular student groups vis a vis targeting change in institutional culture and competency?</em> The session will also feature a discussion with college leaders about strategies that are showing promise.</p><p>Facilitators</p><ul><li>Kay McClenney, Achieving the Dream Leadership Coach and Director, Center for Community College Student Engagement, TX</li><li>Evelyn Waiwaiole, Project Manager, Initiative on Men of Color (CCCSE), TX</li><li>Arleen Arnsparger, Project Manager, Initiative on Student Success (CCCSE), TX</li></ul><p>Leaders/Practitioners</p><ul><li>Richard Armenta, Associate Vice President, Student Success Austin Community College, TX (invited)</li><li>Michael Poindexter, Vice President for Student Services, Sacramento City College, CA (invited)</li><li>Dan Phelan, President, Jackson Community College, MI (invited)</li></ul><p><em>This workshop is fully sponsored by the Kresge Foundation. </em></p><p><a href=\"#top\">^ top</a></p><h2><a name=\"B\"></a>Workshop B: Introduction to Carnegie&#39;s Networked Improvement Community on Developmental Math</h2><p><strong>Tuesday, February 5, 9:00am - 12:00pm</strong></p><p>Advance Registration and Ticket Required: Fee &ndash; Complimentary<br />Continental breakfast (8 &ndash; 9 AM) included for workshop attendees</p><p>The Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching launched its two pathway math courses in Fall 2011. Please join us to learn of our astonishing results and how you might join this community of math faculty improving the teaching and learning of mathematics that has results in tripling the success rate of development students completing college math in one-third the time! In Statway, one no longer needs to imagine that developmental math students can complete a college-level math course with a success rate of 52% in a year when the national average is 5% for one year and 15% for three years, because it now has been done by a group of community colleges working as part of Carnegie&#39;s Networked improvement Community. In Quantway, imagine developmental students finishing the developmental sequence with a 54% success rate in one semester, compared with a national average of 8% in one year or two semesters. This is hard, but innovative work. Join us if you are interested in working differently to achieve greater student success.</p><p>Presenters</p><ul><li>Bernadine Chuck Fong, Achieving the Dream Leadership Coach and Senior Managing Partner, Community College Programs and National Expansion, Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, CA</li><li>Karon Klipple, Senior Associate, Community College Programs&#39; National Expansion, and Director of Statway, Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, CA</li><li>Cinnamon Hillyard, Associate, Director of Quantway&trade;, Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, CA</li><li>Jane Muhich, Senior Associate, Managing Director for Community College Program Development, and Director, Productive Persistence, Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, CA</li><li>Lawrence Morales, Associate, Improvement Research, Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, CA</li></ul><p><em>This workshop is fully sponsored by the Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching.</em></p><p><em>PLEASE NOTE: This workshop will be repeated in the afternoon from 1 PM - 4 PM.</em></p><p><a href=\"#top\">^ top</a></p><h2><a name=\"C\"></a>Workshop C: Bringing Learning Communities to Scale: From Some to More to Most</h2><p><strong>Tuesday, February 5, 9:00am - 4:00pm</strong></p><p>Advance Registration and Ticket Required: Fee - $150.00<br />Continental breakfast (8 &ndash; 9 AM) and lunch (12 &ndash; 1 PM) included for workshop attendees</p><p>How can learning communities, designed for particular students, be &ldquo;scaled up&rdquo; to benefit more and eventually most students, without watering down the very qualities which make thoughtfully implemented learning communities a high-impact practice? Throughout the workshop, we will grapple with the tension between quantity and quality through an exploration of how three Achieving the Dream Institutions&mdash; Kingsborough Community College in New York, Skagit Valley College in Washington, and Valencia College in Florida&mdash; brought their learning communities to scale. We will use More to Most , the MDC guidebook based on lessons learned from the first wave of ATD Institutions to examine how to grow programs beyond the pilot phase. We will also draw from tools developed by the campuses to surface commonalities among the approaches taken by these acknowledged leading institutions in the learning communities field whose student body size and longevity of their learning community programs vary. If you are wondering about the role learning communities can play in turning access into college completion for first-generation, low-income students, this session will deepen your understanding of how learning communities can become an institutional strategy for improving student success. If you have learning communities on your campus, this session will help you think through the moves involved in scaling up learning communities and the scaling strategies you can use.</p><p>Presenters</p><ul><li>Nicholas Bekas, Director, Developmental Education Initiative, Valencia College, FL</li><li>Robin Brighton, Coordinator Learning in Community (LinC) Program, Valencia College, FL</li><li>Emily Decker Lardner, Co-Director, Washington Center for Improving the Quality of Undergraduate Education, The Evergreen State College, WA</li><li>Gillies Malnarich, Co-Director, Washington Center for Improving the Quality of Undergraduate Education, The Evergreen State College, WA</li><li>Linda Moore, English Faculty, Skagit Valley College, WA</li><li>Maureen Pettitt, Director of Institutional Research, Skagit Valley College, WA</li><li>Marissa Schlesinger, Director of Academic Affairs, Kingsborough Community College, NY</li><li>Cheryl Smith, Professor, Kingsborough Community College, NY</li><li>Linda Moore, English Faculty, Skagit Valley College, WA</li></ul><p><a href=\"#top\">^ top</a></p><h2><a name=\"D\"></a>Workshop D: Engaging Your Board for Student Success</h2><p><strong>Tuesday, February 5, 9:00am - 4:00pm</strong></p><p>Advance Registration and Ticket Required: Fee - $150<br />Continental breakfast (8 &ndash; 9 AM) and lunch (12 &ndash; 1 PM) included for workshop attendees</p><p>The Community College Leadership Program (CCLP) at The University of Texas at Austin joins Achieving the Dream, Inc. (ATD) in inviting 25 Board Chair/CEO teams to a six-hour pre-meeting workshop at DREAM 2013. This interactive session will provide the opportunity to learn from the experiences and learnings from 18 trustee institutes held since 2007, which were focused on the student success agenda. You will hear about the critical role being played by boards in creating the culture within which a CEO can provide courageous leadership. You will leave with an action plan to engage other board members upon your return home. Come see how to get beyond buildings, budgets, and bonds (and personnel) to create a robust student success agenda. The session will be led by Dr. Byron McClenney, National Director of Leadership Coaching for Achieving the Dream. He also partners with ACCT to deliver the Governance Institute for Student Success (GISS).</p><p>Presenter</p><ul><li>Byron McClenney, National Director of Leadership Coaching for Achieving the Dream and Achieving the Dream Leadership Coach, TX</li></ul><p><em>First come, first served. Limited to 25 teams.</em></p><p><a href=\"#top\">^ top</a></p><h2><a name=\"E\"></a>Workshop E: Using ATD Tools to Advance Equity and Reduce Achievement Gaps</h2><p><strong>Tuesday, February 5, 1:00pm - 4:00pm</strong></p><p>Advance Registration and Ticket Required: Fee &ndash; $25<br />Lunch (12 &ndash; 1 PM) included for workshop attendees</p><p>This workshop is for college faculty and staff teams (teams of two or more are encouraged but not required) who want to increase student success and reduce achievement gaps in their institutions. It features three Achieving the Dream tools that support the processes of recognizing and assessing the structural inequities that can make college completion especially difficult for particular groups of students. Tools include: (1) Increasing Student Success: Why Equity Matters (video), (2) The Finish Line (a simulation), and (3) The Inventory on Diversity and Equity (an assessment tool). Participants will discuss their experiences exploring issues of equity and begin creating an action plan for advancing equity in their own institutions. Participants in this highly interactive workshop will gain an understanding of the ATD equity tools, greater comfort in using them, and a &ldquo;next steps&rdquo; action plan for discussing and increasing equity at their institution.</p><p>Presenters</p><ul><li>Eileen Baccus, Achieving the Dream Leadership Coach, FL</li><li>Lynda Villanueva, Achieving the Dream Data Coach and Associate Dean of Instruction, Brazosport College, TX</li></ul><p><a href=\"#top\">^ top</a></p><h2><a name=\"F\"></a>Workshop F: Orchestrating the Use of Data: Data Summits as the Launch</h2><p><strong>Tuesday, February 5, 1:00pm - 4:00pm</strong></p><p>Advance Registration and Ticket Required: Fee - $150<br />Lunch (12 &ndash; 1 PM) included for workshop attendees</p><p>This workshop blends theories of analytics, organizational behavior, and human judgment and decision-making with practical examples of how to move a college to actually use its data. We perceive the Data Summit as the launch, not the end. We contend that data are too often perceived as hammers to punish rather than tools to improve, and that too many data presentations are dense, dry, and divert attention from the core message. Workshop participants will leave with a better understanding of how we perceive and process data and information (the theory part), as well as strategies and data presentation examples to increase use of data throughout the organization (the practical part).</p><p>Presenters</p><ul><li>Trudy Bers, Achieving the Dream Data Coach and Executive Director, Research, Curriculum and Planning at Oakton Community College, IL</li><li>Brad Phillips, Achieving the Dream Data Coach and President/CEO, Institute for Evidence-Based Change, CA</li></ul><p><a href=\"#top\">^ top</a></p><h2><a name=\"G\"></a>Workshop G: Phi Theta Kappa/DREAMbassadors: A Student-Led Alliance for College Completion</h2><p><strong>Tuesday, February 5, 1:00pm - 4:00pm</strong></p><p>Advance Registration and Ticket Required: Fee - $150<br />Lunch (12 &ndash; 1 PM) included for workshop attendees</p><p>As the only student organization to sign &ldquo;Democracy&rsquo;s Colleges Call to Action&rdquo; to increase community college completion rates, Phi Theta Kappa has mobilized its 1,280 chapters as a Community College Completion Corps (C4) to help engage all two-year college students in building a culture of completion. Achieving the Dream&rsquo;s DREAMbassadors at select colleges have worked alongside their campus&rsquo; Phi Theta Kappa chapters to further strengthen this alliance. Phi Theta Kappa Executive Director Dr. Rod Risley and the inaugural DREAMbassadors will share their most promising practices, most valuable resources, and some lessons learned in their work to successfully impact the college completion agenda across the country.</p><p>Presenters</p><ul style=\"\"><li>Rod Risley, Executive Director of Phi Theta Kappa</li><li>2012-2013 DREAMbassadors<ul><li>Robert Ramirez, Brazosport College, TX</li><li>Elizabeth Davis, Tarrant County College, TX</li><li>Sam Jones, University of the District of Columbia Community College, DC</li><li>Sandra Valley Bagley, Phillips Community College of the University of Arkansas, AR</li></ul></li></ul><p><a href=\"#top\">^ top</a></p><h2><a name=\"H\"></a>Workshop H: Introduction to Carnegie&#39;s Networked Improvement Community on Developmental Math</h2><p><strong>Tuesday, February 5, 1:00pm - 4:00pm</strong></p><p>Advance Registration and Ticket Required: Fee &ndash; Complimentary<br />Lunch (12 - 1 PM) included for workshop attendees</p><p>The Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching launched its two pathway math courses in Fall 2011. Please join us to learn of our astonishing results and how you might join this community of math faculty improving the teaching and learning of mathematics that has results in tripling the success rate of development students completing college math in one-third the time! In Statway, one no longer needs to imagine that developmental math students can complete a college-level math course with a success rate of 52% in a year when the national average is 5% for one year and 15% for three years, because it now has been done by a group of community colleges working as part of Carnegie&#39;s Networked improvement Community. In Quantway, imagine developmental students finishing the developmental sequence with a 54% success rate in one semester, compared with a national average of 8% in one year or two semesters. This is hard, but innovative work. Join us if you are interested in working differently to achieve greater student success.</p><p>Presenters</p><ul><li>Bernadine Chuck Fong, Achieving the Dream Leadership Coach and Senior Managing Partner, Community College Programs and National Expansion, Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, CA</li><li>Karon Klipple, Senior Associate, Community College Programs&#39; National Expansion, and Director of Statway, Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, CA</li><li>Cinnamon Hillyard, Associate, Director of Quantway&trade;, Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, CA</li><li>Jane Muhich, Senior Associate, Managing Director for Community College Program Development, and Director, Productive Persistence, Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, CA</li><li>Lawrence Morales, Associate, Improvement Research, Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, CA</li></ul><p><em>This workshop is fully sponsored by the Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching.</em></p><p><em>PLEASE NOTE: This is a repeat of Workshop B.</em></p><p><a href=\"#top\">^ top</a></p><h2><a name=\"I\"></a>Workshop I: Building a Successful Prior Learning Assessment (PLA) Program in Partnership</h2><p><strong>February 5, 1:00pm - 4:00pm</strong></p><p>Advance Registration and Ticket Required: Fee - Complimentary<br />Lunch (12 &ndash; 1 PM) included for workshop attendees</p><p>The session will provide participants with a practical understanding of the critical steps involved in implementing a new PLA program, galvanizing a program that is already on the books, or growing an existing PLA program to include alternative options for earning credit. Tools and resources will be provided to help participants get started. Participants will also learn how colleges can outsource or augment their existing PLA program using LearningCounts, a complete PLA solution that provides PLA advising, credit and non-credit PLA portfolio building courses, CAEL trained assessors, and an integrated course and portfolio development environment for students.</p><p>Presenters</p><ul><li>Judith Wertheim, Vice President for Higher Education Services, CAEL</li><li>Vicki Ancell, Director of Strategic Partnerships, LearningCounts.org, CAEL</li><li>Representative(s) from LearningCounts.org community college partner institution(s)</li></ul><p><em>This workshop is fully sponsored by The Council for Adult Experiential Learning. </em></p><p><a href=\"#top\">^ top</a></p><h2><a name=\"J\"></a>Workshop J: Faculty Development: Keys to Scaling Up Acceleration in Developmental Writing</h2><p><strong>Tuesday, February 5, 1:00pm - 4:00pm</strong></p><p>Advance Registration and Ticket Required: Fee - $150<br />Lunch (12 &ndash; 1 PM) included for workshop attendees</p><p>Pedagogy is key to accelerated models of developmental education. At the Community College of Baltimore County (CCBC), we have found that faculty development and what happens in the classroom are as important as the structural model. We recognize that most faculty teaching developmental writing were educated to teach literature and seldom have taken more than one or two courses in teaching writing. In this workshop we will discuss the multifaceted approach to developmental education that we have followed in the Accelerated Learning Program (ALP) at CCBC to assist your college in implementing similar faculty development for accelerated models of developmental education. Participants will learn about:</p><ul><li>How teaching in an ALP class differs from traditional teaching.</li><li>Various modes of faculty development: 20-hour institutes, on-line faculty communities, mentoring, half-day workshops, and informal drop-in sessions. Assumptions behind successful faculty development: respecting faculty autonomy, recognizing there can be more than one effective pedagogy, allowing faculty to try out challenging changes, and emphasizing practical applications in the classroom.</li><li>Topics addressed during faculty development events: backward curriculum design, active learning, integrating reading and writing, improving thinking skills, culturally sensitive pedagogy, addressing non-cognitive issues, coordinating the credit and the developmental courses.</li><li>A state-wide faculty development effort in Michigan.</li></ul><p>Presenters</p><ul><li>Peter Adams, Director of Accelerated Learning Program, Community College of Baltimore County, MD</li><li>Susan Gabriel, Associate Professor, English Department, Community College of Baltimore County, MD</li><li>Jenny Schanker, Associate Director, Center for Student Success Michigan Community College Association, MI</li><li>David DeBaker, Assistant Professor, Jackson Community College, MI</li></ul><p><a href=\"#top\">^ top</a></p>','','filtered_html');
