INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','person',0,4046,9626,'und',0,'<p>Jessica Thompkins is an AmericCorps VISTA serving as the Community Engagement Coordinator at Achieving the Dream Inc.&nbsp; In this role, Jessica is working to build the organization&rsquo;s community engagement capacity. Currently, she is helping the Community College of Baltimore County build the college&rsquo;s capability to refine, expand, and improve financial education programming for students. &nbsp;She will recruit, motivate, and coordinate skilled volunteers to reach program goals and also build knowledge and lay the foundation for adoption of more comprehensive solutions to helping low income college students achieve academic security. &nbsp;She also works to build Achieving the Dream&rsquo;s community engagement capacity.<br /><br />Prior to her role at Achieving the Dream, she served with City Year as a Corps Member and Community Engagement Coordinator in an elementary school in Washington, DC. As a Corps Member, Jessica assisted in a in a 3<sup>rd </sup>grade classroom, held literacy interventions for 2<sup>nd</sup> and 3<sup>rd</sup> graders, and math interventions for 3<sup>rd</sup> graders. In the role of Community Engagement Coordinator, Jessica was able to work with organizations throughout Washington, DC to hold events for the students and their families such as Science Night, Earth Day, Reading with Red Jackets, and a Halloween Extravaganza.<br /><br />Education background: Jessica holds a Bachelor of Science in Communications with a concentration in Organizational Communication and a minor in Recreation and Leisure from The College at Brockport, State University of New York.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','person',0,4047,9628,'und',0,'<p>Alexandra Roose is the Assistant Director of Communications for Achieving the Dream, Inc. In this role, Alexandra supports the development of online and print materials, assists with media relations, and coordinates a variety of student engagement efforts.</p><p>Prior to her role with Achieving the Dream, Alexandra served as a Senior Account Executive at Hager Sharp, where she created a large variety of outreach publications and developed impactful social media strategies. She has also served as a communications consultant to the Annie E. Casey Foundation for a variety of its portfolios.</p><p>Educational Background:&nbsp; Alexandra graduated Magna Cum Laude from Towson University, where she earned a Bachelor of Arts in Mass Communications and Public Relations.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','person',0,4048,9629,'und',0,'<p>Elyssa Shildneck is the Communications and Executive Intern at Achieving the Dream. In her role as the Communications Intern, Elyssa manages Achieving the Dream&rsquo;s social media portfolio, assists with website maintenance, and provides overall support to the communications team. As the Executive Intern, Elyssa assists the Chief Operating Officer in evaluating applicants for open positions, and provides support to the Executive Assistant and CEO.&nbsp;</p><p>Immediately before coming to Achieving the Dream, Elyssa served as the Fellowships and Grants Intern for the American Association of University Women. In this role, Elyssa contributed weekly to the AAUW Dialog through her Following the Fellows Series on past AAUW Fellows and Grantees.&nbsp; She shed light on women&rsquo;s accomplishments and hardships in a variety of fields including athletics and STEM. Elyssa has also interned for Congresswoman Rosa DeLauro and Congressman Alan Grayson. While completing her bachelor&rsquo;s degree at University of Connecticut, Elyssa served as a tutor for the Counseling Program for Intercollegiate Athletes, where she became interested in student success.</p><p>Educational Background: Elyssa holds a Bachelor of Arts in Political Science with a minor in Anthropology from the University of Connecticut and she is currently pursuing her Master&rsquo;s in Public Administration from American University, concentrating on social policy with a focus on education.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','news',0,4049,9630,'und',0,'<h3>$215,000 grant will allow PHCC to expand successful interventions within college and across the nation</h3><p>Patrick Henry Community College was selected as one of four community colleges nationwide to participate in the new Catalyst Fund grant program and will receive a $215,000 grant.</p><p>The application process for the Catalyst Fund grants was extremely competitive, and the fact that PHCC is among only four in the country to receive one is &ldquo;a point of pride for our community,&rdquo; according to PHCC President Angeline Godwin.</p><p>Catalyst Fund grants are administered by Achieving the Dream, Inc., a national nonprofit leading the nation&rsquo;s most comprehensive non-governmental reform network for community college student success, with support from the Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation. PHCC was selected because of its known commitment to student-centered, evidence-based reforms and outstanding increases in student outcomes.</p><p>&ldquo;Patrick Henry Community College is recognized as a leader in the Achieving the Dream National Reform Network for its proven success and commitment to student achievement,&rdquo; said Rachel Singer, Vice President for Community College Relations and Applied Research, Achieving the Dream, Inc. &ldquo;The effective practices Patrick Henry has chosen to scale will yield important information and lessons which will be used to inform the field.&rdquo;</p><p>PHCC is known as a Leader College based on successes in student persistence and graduation rates through the use of cooperative learning. The college became an Achieving the Dream (AtD) college in 2004 as one of 26 community colleges in the nation to pilot the program, funded by the Lumina Foundation. Demonstrated success with AtD facilitated PHCC to become one of 15 community colleges in the country to receive a Developmental Education Initiative grant from the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation in 2009. That grant allowed PHCC to continue and broaden the scope of its cooperative education program, which in turn paved the way for this latest grant from the Gates Foundation.</p><p>Armed with a Catalyst grant, PHCC has an opportunity to make an even greater impact on student success and will focus attention on the ever-growing number of students enrolled in online classes. The college will use the funds to implement cooperative learning strategies in the online environment, as well as training faculty at other community colleges across the country. To date, PHCC has trained faculty at more than 40 community colleges nationwide.</p><p>&ldquo;This generous grant from the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation will help Patrick Henry Community College leverage its already successful cooperative learning program to serve even more PHCC students,&rdquo; Godwin said. &ldquo;We now engage and see success with more than half of our students through cooperative learning. This grant will allow us to increase that to three quarters.&rdquo;</p><p>The Achieving the Dream National Reform Network is committed to investigating ways to scale effective interventions to ensure that more, and ultimately most, students attain the skills and credentials necessary for success in the global economy. Beginning with PHCC, the Catalyst Fund will support the expansion of programs and policies that support widespread scaling &ndash; both within the colleges and to other community colleges across the nation.</p><p>&ldquo;Postsecondary completion is one of the Gates Foundation&rsquo;s major priorities,&rdquo; said Suzanne Walsh, Senior Program Officer, Postsecondary Success at the Gates Foundation. &ldquo;We want to see most students who enroll in a community college complete what they started. Achieving the Dream Colleges have a great tradition of working with students in an intense way and effectively using evidence to guide their decision-making process. We are pleased to fund this critical initiative to scale proven interventions.&rdquo;</p><p>As part of the Catalyst Fund, PHCC will work to scale its proven interventions through the Achieving the Dream Student Centered Model of Institutional Improvement, which is based upon four critical principles: committed leadership, use of evidence to improve programs and services, broad engagement, and systematic institutional improvement. Additionally, the college will work to scale its interventions in a systematic way, so that the interventions may be embedded in the institutions&rsquo; framework for sustainability.</p><p>Lessons learned from Patrick Henry will help inform best practices for scaling interventions to better inform the Achieving the Dream National Reform Network and community colleges across the nation.</p><p>Godwin and several faculty and staff at PHCC have convened with Achieving the Dream and the other three colleges for an inaugural Catalyst Fund Kickoff Institute at the Sheraton in Silver Spring, MD on November 15 &ndash; November 16.</p><p>The following are all four Achieving the Dream Leader Colleges that will each receive a $215,000 grant to spur the expansion of proven interventions at the heart of their student success work.</p><ul><li>Brazosport College (Lake Jackson, TX)</li><li>Bunker Hill Community College (Boston, MA)</li><li>Durham Technical Community College (Durham, NC)</li><li>Patrick Henry Community College (Martinsville, VA)</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Achieving the Dream Leader Colleges</p><p>Leader Colleges are demonstrating the power of the Achieving the Dream Student-Centered Model of Institutional Improvement. They show that it is possible to raise persistence and graduation rates, close achievement gaps, and improve lives. Leader Colleges represent the ultimate goal of Achieving the Dream, and as such, support other institutions within a community of learners. To be eligible for Leader College distinction, colleges must demonstrate commitment to and progress on the Achieving the Dream principles: committed leadership, use of evidence to improve programs and services, broad engagement, and systemic institutional improvement. They must also show three years of sustained improvement of student success on at least one of the following measures of performance:</p><ul><li>Completion of certificates or degrees</li><li>Term-to-term and year-to-year retention</li><li>Completion of college-level math and English courses</li><li>Advancement from developmental to credit-bearing courses</li><li>Course completion</li></ul>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','news',0,4050,9637,'und',0,'<p>Six SPC students are among more than 100 community college students competing nationwide for a shot at scholarship awards in Achieving the Dream&rsquo;s ongoing video contest.</p><p>Voting now is open for the public to select their top picks among participants. The top 10 will then be reviewed by a panel of judges who will choose who will be the final three. The first place winner will receive $1,500, second place gets $1,000 and third place will be awarded $500. Public voting ends Nov. 28. One vote per voter. Winners will be announced on or before Dec. 5, according to contest rules.</p><p>See all of the <a href=\"http://dreambig.maker.good.is/projects.dreambig\">contest submissions</a> or take a look at the six videos submitted by SPC students and support them in their efforts to finish in the top three:</p><ul><li><a href=\"http://dreambig.maker.good.is/projects/jshea\">American Dream </a></li><li><a href=\"http://dreambig.maker.good.is/projects/BryceChester\">A Dream Undeterred</a></li><li><a href=\"http://dreambig.maker.good.is/projects/VeraVeritas\">Expose: The secret is thinking positive and knowing that there is a light at the end of the tunnel</a></li><li><a href=\"http://dreambig.maker.good.is/projects/NicoleV123\">To Help the Community</a></li><li><a href=\"http://dreambig.maker.good.is/projects/stylecitymusic\">Video production major &ndash; St. Petersburg College</a></li><li><a href=\"http://dreambig.maker.good.is/projects/marussek\">A Wild Dream</a></li></ul><p>Contest organizers asked students to tell them, in a video, about their dream job and how their college was helping them get there.</p><p>Achieving the Dream is a national nonprofit dedicated to helping more community college students stay in school and earn a college certificate or degree.</p>','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','news',0,4051,9641,'und',0,'<p>The Postsecondary State Policy Network &ndash; the work of the non-profit Achieving the Dream, Inc. &ndash; is welcoming five additional states &ndash; Connecticut, Hawaii, Massachusetts, Oklahoma and Virginia, with these additions bringing the number of states participating in the PSPN to 11.</p><p>The goal of the network is to determine which policies &ndash; be they administrative, system or legislative &ndash; will best promote the aim of institutional reform in higher education. The secondary goal is to put down pathways that students can follow when working towards completion of their college degree. The network also aims to spread these reform strategies, lessons and resultant models across the states.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.achievingthedream.org/\">Achieving the Dream</a> is collaborating with <a href=\"http://www.jff.org/\">Jobs for the Future</a> to join network participants and to have them working together, and sharing their experiences, all in an effort to raise their respective college graduation rates.</p><blockquote><p>One way that state policy teams will spread promising practices, challenges, and lessons learned is through cross-state meetings. The first of those meetings will take place November 27 in Boston, MA.</p><p>Representatives from the states, Achieving the Dream, and Jobs for the Future will be in attendance. Attendees will discuss their work; specifically, how they will improve student services so more students can succeed in college. In the coming year, Achieving the Dream supported states will pursue a range of evidence-based reform initiatives, from piloting performance-based scholarships and improving transfer success, to fundamentally transforming the delivery of developmental education. These reforms are crucial in meeting the national demand for a more college-educated citizenry.</p></blockquote><p>Community college systems all over the country are experiencing tremendous difficulties at the moment as they balance an ever-growing number of students with ever-shrinking state education budgets. The states that have joined the PSPN recognize that a time of difficulty such as this is also a time of opportunity to bring about sweeping reform in how community college systems deliver education to their students.</p><blockquote><p>&ldquo;While a significant number of the students walking through the community college front door may not be college-ready, Achieving the Dream and our National Reform Network believe that all students walking through the door are college-material,&rdquo; said Carol Lincoln, Senior Vice President, Achieving the Dream. &ldquo;We will work closely with our policy states to ensure that the reforms are guided by our values of equity, excellence, and evidence.&rdquo;</p></blockquote><p>Achieving the Dream has been committed to policy reform as a means to achieving its goal of community college success for an increasing number of students nationwide, and it sees working with Jobs for the Future as important to creating an environment in community colleges that will make it possible for students to succeed.</p>','','filtered_html');
